# Global Agent Instructions

## Version Control

- If a repo has `.jj` (Jujutsu initialized), prefer `jj` over `git` for all write operations (commit, describe, push, bookmark, etc.).
- Read operations (diff, log, status) can use either, but prefer `jj` for consistency.
- Use `jj describe` instead of `git commit`, `jj new` instead of `git checkout -b`, `jj bookmark set` + `jj push` instead of `git push`, etc.
- Use `jj git push` to push changes.
- For sub-agents that need isolated working copies, use `jj workspace add /tmp/workspace-name` instead of `git worktree`. Clean up with `jj workspace forget` and `rm -rf` the tmp directory when done.

### Commit discipline

**Never squash commits.** Always prefer multiple, well-described commits. Squashing destroys reviewer context and makes `git blame` / `jj log` useless. Each logical change gets its own commit with a clear message.

Use `jj new -m "message"` to start the next commit. If a change needs to be split, use `jj split [FILESETS...]` by path — never interactively.

### Pushing to PRs under review

jj rewrites commit SHAs on any mutation (describe, squash, rebase), which means
`jj git push` is always a force push. GitHub tracks review state by commit SHA,
so force pushes destroy reviewer context: "viewed" markers reset, inline
comments get orphaned, and the "Changes since last review" diff breaks.

**Before pushing, check if the branch has an open PR with reviews:**

```bash
# For github.com repos:
gh pr list --head "$(jj bookmark list --all -T 'if(self.tracked(), name ++ "\n")' | head -1)" --json number,reviewDecision,reviews --jq '.[0]'

# For code.vastspace.com repos:
GH_HOST=code.vastspace.com gh pr list --head "$(jj bookmark list --all -T 'if(self.tracked(), name ++ "\n")' | head -1)" --json number,reviewDecision,reviews --jq '.[0]'
```

**If the PR has reviews:**

- **Add new commits on top** with `jj new -m "address review feedback"`. Do
  not amend, squash into, or rebase already-pushed commits.
- **Do not rebase onto main/trunk** unless there are conflicts or the user
  explicitly asks. An unnecessary rebase rewrites every commit in the stack.
- **Do not `jj describe`** on already-pushed commits (it rewrites their SHA).
- **Warn the user** before any push that will force-push over reviewed commits.
  Explain what reviewer context will be lost.

**If the PR has no reviews yet**, normal jj workflow applies (amend, rebase,
describe freely).

### Multi-agent jj workflow

Workspaces give each agent an isolated working copy while sharing the same repo. All changes are visible in `jj log` from any workspace.

1. Note your current change: `jj log --limit 1`
2. Per agent: `jj workspace add /tmp/agent-<task>`, then `jj new <parent> -m "task"`
3. Agent works (all edits auto-tracked, no staging needed)
4. When done, from your main workspace: `jj rebase -r <agent-change> -d <target>` to land the change as its own commit
5. To combine multiple agents as a merge: `jj new <change-a> <change-b>`
6. Clean up: `jj workspace forget <name> && rm -rf /tmp/agent-<task>`

For sequential (non-parallel) agents, skip workspaces. Just `jj new -m "task"` before each agent runs.

### Non-interactive jj usage

Never use `-i`/`--interactive` flags or commands that open an editor/diff tool. These hang in agent sessions.

- `jj describe -m "message"` sets the description without opening an editor.
- `jj split [FILESETS...]` splits by paths, not interactively. Without paths it opens a diff editor, so always provide paths.
- `jj new -m "message"` creates a new change without opening an editor.
- `jj rebase -r <rev> -d <dest>` moves a commit without squashing it.
- Always pass `-m` to any command that would otherwise open `$EDITOR`.

## Personal Notes

The `.matan/` directory is gitignored globally and is the conventional place for personal notes, scratch files, and local context that should never be committed. Feel free to create or read `.matan/` in any repo for repo-specific notes.

## GitHub CLI

- Never use `gh` (or `GH_HOST=... gh`) to post, reply to, or leave comments on PRs or issues unless explicitly asked.
- This includes `gh pr comment`, `gh pr review`, `gh issue comment`, and similar write operations.
- Read operations (`gh pr view`, `gh pr diff`, `gh issue list`, etc.) are always fine.

